1 Overview of workshop

1.1 Objectives

  • To understand the importance of data/analysis transparency and to learn practical data management practices like version control and project directory structure
  • To understand what GitHub is useful for in this regard, and how to use it
  • To learn how to set up a computer for bioinformatic and statistical analyses in R Studio*
  • To learn how to access and retrieve next generation sequencing data from NCBIs Short Read Archive
  • To understand the data types and structures involved in RNA-seq and differential gene expression analyses; what sequencing reads and gene expression count matrices are, and how to work with them
  • To understand differential gene expression analysis results and how to visualize them to tell a story
  • To learn how to write and work with markdown documents for reproducible data analysis
  • To learn how to utilize publisher-provided LATEX typesets for formatting analyses (and our stories informed by them) for publication.

3 Session 1: Initial setup and discussion over data transparency, management, and reproducibility

We will be focusing on data management strategies for a reproducible analysis and output workflow to facilitate transparent and reproducible research as well as support open data sharing.

More specifically, in this session you will learn how to:

  1. Document your data for reusability and structure tabular data for computation.
  2. Manage and organize your files using a project structure.
  3. Utilize the version control software, Git, in the RStudio environment.
  4. Implement a reproducible, project- based, data analysis and output workflow in RStudio.

3.2 Data Management Basics

Implementing a project folder structure that you use consistently along with a file naming system is good practice as it allows you to easily navigate project contents.

3.2.1 File and object naming:

Using file and object naming conventions will help you more effectively find and use your data.

Some naming best practices include:

  • Create brief yet meaningful names
  • Avoid using spaces, dots, and special characters (&, ?, !), instead use hypthens (-) or underscores (-)
  • When files are linked in a workflow, number them to indicate the order they should be run
  • Denote versioning where appropriate

3.2.2 Project Structure:

Project structure and descriptions adapted from Cookiecutter Data Science, R Best Practices by Krista L. DeStasio), & project_template GitHub repository - Drew Wham

Below is an example project folder structure:

Named_Project/

|README.md

|R_Project

|volume/

| |data/

| | |raw

| | |interim

| | |external

|required

| |requirements.R

|source_code/

|documents/

|figures/

|output/

|.gitignore

  • Named_Project: Root level folder denoting the project. This folder contains all folders and files related to the project and is checked into GitHub.
  • README.md: Top-level README file outlining folder structure and files as well as file associations.
  • R_Project: A R_Project file.
  • Volume: A folder containing your data subset by type. This folder will not be uploaded to Github thus we will .gitignore it.
  • Data: This folder contains data subfolders. Within this folder, are the data you will use for analysis. - Raw: Raw data files used in the project. These files should be treated as read-only and never altered. - Interim: Intermediate data that has been wrangled or transformed. - External: Data from third-party sources.
  • Required: The required libraries for reproducing the R environment.
  • Source_code: Source code or scripts for running data wrangling, analysis, and visualization.
  • Documents: Generated documents for final reporting of the project such as manuscripts or reports.
  • Figures: Generated figures for final reporting of the project. This should only contain figures generated by your saved source code.
  • Output: Non-figure objects created by your source code including processed data, logs, simulation output, or model output.
  • .gitignore: List of files not to sync with GitHub.

3.2.3 Setting up a RStudio Project

Why use a RStudio Project?

Using a RStudio Project is an easy way to keep everything you need for your analysis together in a manner that is reproducible and shareable.

It is best practice to avoid using absolute paths, such as those implemented using the setwd() approach, because the link to this location can easily be broken and is not easily reproduced by others. Jenny Bryan explains this by stating The chance of the setwd() command having the desired effect - making the file paths work - for anyone besides its author is 0%. Its also unlikely to work for the author one or two years or computers from now. The project is not self-contained and portable. To recreate and perhaps extend this plot, the lucky recipient will need to hand edit one or more paths to reflect where the project has landed on their machine ( Project-oriented workflow by Jenny Bryan )

Using RStudio Projects allows you to use relative paths rather than absolute paths and store settings for a particular project. An RStudio Project relative path points to the top level folder where your .Rproj file is located.

How to set up an RStudio Project:

  1. Click the R Project: (None) button in the top right corner of the RStudio console.
  2. Select New Directory
  3. Select New Project
  4. Give your directory a name and locate where on your computer you want this project directory and RStudio project to be stored
  5. Click Create Project
3.2.3.0.1 Exercise 1:
  1. Navigate to your project folder on your desktop. Look through each of the folders and consider what you would put in each.
  2. Open RStudio and using the below directions, designate this folder as your project folder.
    • Open RStudio.
    • Click the RProject button in the top right of the console.
    • Select New Project.
    • Select Existing Directory.
    • Browse to the Project folder on your Desktop and select this folder.
    • Click Create Project.

3.3 Key Elements For Good R Code

  1. It is a bad habit to rely on the settings of a previous RStudio session. To prevent RStudio from saving your settings from a previous session, you can change the following setting:
  • Find your preferences in RStudio
  • Under the general tab
    • Uncheck Restore .RData
    • Select never for Save workspace

( R for Data Science by Wickham & Grolemund, Project-oriented workflow by Jenny Bryan )

  1. Make your code readable.
  • Organize your code to make it more readable.
    • Start your code with a brief description of what it does.
    • Make run requirements and dependencies clear by putting library() loading and functions at the top.
  • Use comments to describe the purpose of the code
  • Use meaningful object naming
  • Use version control
  • Adopt a coding style

( Why I want to write nice R cod by Daniel Falster, R Best Practices by Krista L. DeStasio )

  1. Make your code reliable
  • Check that your code is error free

( Why I want to write nice R cod by Daniel Falster )

3.4 Version Control with Git and GitHub

Instructions below are either from or adapted from Happy Git and GitHub for the useR by Jennifer Bryan.

3.4.1 Configure Git with your user credentials:

*Windows users will want to use the Git Bash shell!

In the shell or terminal, type the following with your name and email as they are associated with your GitHub account:

git config --global user.name enteryournamehere

git config --global user.email enteryouremailhere

Confirm that you have configured Git with your credentials, using the following code in the shell or terminal:

Git config --global --list

3.4.2 Connect to GitHub:

  1. Login to GitHub at https://github.com
  2. Create a new repository by either clicking the New repository button or from your personal profile clicking Repositories > New
  3. You will be prompted to:
    • Name your repository: Set your repository name to CFH_RWorkshop2
    • Add a description: Include the following text: testing setup
    • Select private as the visibility
    • Select to initialize this repository with a README
  4. Create the repository
  5. By clicking the Clone or Download button, copy the HTTPS clone URL.

3.4.3 Clone GitHub repository on your computer in RStudio:

  1. Open RStudio
  2. Start a new project in RStudio: File > New Project > Version Control > Git.
  3. Under Repository URL, paste the copy of the HTTPS clone URL for your GitHub repository you created above.
  4. Check that the default project directory name matches the name of your GitHub repository and accept.
  5. Note where the R Project will be saved locally.
  6. Select Open in new session
  7. Click Create Project
  8. Check that you can see the GitHub README.md in the RStudio file browser pane.
  • Connecting RStudio to Git can be complicated because of variability between operating systems and versions of operating systems. To confirm that Git properly setup, follow the following steps:

Mac OS

  1. In RStudio, select Preferences > Git/SVN
  2. Check to see if a path to a file in the Git executable window exists.
  3. If not, return to your shell or terminal and type which git. This will produce the path to your Git executable if it is installed.
  4. Type or paste in the full path to your git executable: e.g./usr/bin/git into the Git executable box on R Studio Git/SVN screen.

Windows

  1. In RStudio, Go Tools > Global options > Git/SVN
  2. Check to see if a path to a file in the Git executable window exists.
  3. If not, return to your shell or terminal and type which git. This will produce the path to your Git executable if it is installed.
  4. Type or paste in the full path to your git executable: e.g./usr/bin/git into the Git executable box on R Studio Git/SVN screen.
  • If Git is still not properly connected, following this link to see steps to troubleshoot.

3.4.4 Make local changes, save, and commit to Git:

  1. In RStudio, add the line This is a line from RStudio in the README.md file and click save
  2. Click the Git tab in the upper right pane
  3. Check Staged box for README.md
  4. If youre not already in the Git pop-up, click Commit.
  5. Type a message in Commit message, such as Commit from RStudio.
  6. Click Commit

3.4.5 Push your local changes online to GitHub:

  1. Click the green Push button to send your local changes online at GitHub.
  2. Go to GitHub online to confirm that the local change was submitted to GitHub online.

4 Session 2: RNA-seq analysis, from sequencing reads to gene expression count matrices

In this session, we will retrieve (a subset of) sequencing reads from an RNA-seq experiment exploring tissue-specific gene expression profiles of nurse, forager, and winter honey bees. The goal of this experiment was to test hypotheses about the relationship between the winter bee phenotype and diapause, a genetically programmed state of dormancy which is triggered by environmental cues in advance of adverse conditions, such as winter in temperate areas or hot and dry conditions in tropical areas (Denlinger & Armbruster, 2013; Saulich & Musolin, 2017; Sim & Denlinger, 2013). The physiology of winter worker bees (and long-lived summer bees) suggest that they are in a diapause-like state [see Bresnahan et al.in prep i.e., hopefully someday soon :) ]

4.1 Example experiment: methods

Sample collection was conducted as described in (Doke et al., 2019). Briefly, four colonies headed by naturally mated honey bee queens from four different commercial breeders were established at a Pennsylvania State University apiary in central Pennsylvania. Colonies were maintained according to standard apicultural practices. More than 6 weeks after establishment (July 2013), which is sufficient time for the eggs laid by the queens to develop into adult nurses and foragers, 6 summer nurse and forager bees per colony were collected on dry ice and stored at -80\(^\circ\)C. Winter bees were collected 5 months later (December 2013) from within their respective winter clusters.

After removal from storage at -80\(^\circ\)C, sampled bees were submerged in Invitrogen\(^{TM}\) Ambion\(^{TM}\) RNAlater\(^{TM}\) Stabilization Solution (ThermoFisher Scientific) to prevent RNA degradation, and dissected on a platform surrounded by dry ice. To collect flight muscle tissue, legs and wings were detached from thorax and discarded, leaving flight muscles and exoskeleton. To collect abdominal fat body tissues, abdomens were allowed to thaw RNAlater\(^{TM}\) on ice. Digestive tracts and reproductive organs were then removed by gently pulling from the stinger using forceps, leaving the eviscerated abdomen with fat body. Dissected tissues for each worker were individually placed in a 1.5ml nuclease-free microcentrifuge tube (Denville Scientific Inc., Metuchen, NJ) and kept at -80\(^\circ\)C.

For each of the 4 colonies, samples of the same tissue and bee type were pooled (6 bees per sample). Pooled samples (4 colonies x 3 groups x 2 tissues = 24 samples, total) were homogenized using an automated homogenizer (Thermo Savant FastPrep\(^{TM}\) FP120 Cell Disrupter System) for 3 intervals of 45 seconds at the highest speed setting, using 3-6 2mm zirconia bees (BioSpec Products, Inc.). Homogenates were stored for later use in RNA extraction via the RNeasy Plus Universal kit (QIAGEN) for RNA sequencing (RNA-seq). RNA libraries were prepared by the Sequencing and Genomic Technologies Shared Resource at the Duke Center for Genomic and Computational Biology, Durham, NC, and sequenced on an Illumina HiSeq 4000 platform.

4.2 Methods (ClEaRlY eXpLaInEd)

What does all of this mean? If you are super new to RNA-sequencing and Next Generation Sequencing (NGS) technologies in general, please watch this excellent and gentle introduction to RNA-seq by Josh Starmer (previously of North Carolina State University)

  • A gentle introduction to RNA-seq

For reference, here is a workflow diagram depicting a typical RNA-seq experiment. We begin at part III, with the .fastq files generated by the sequencing facility.

An RNA-seq workflow: a typical RNA-seq experiment can be thought of as consisting of 3 main phases: (I) RNA-seq library preparation, (II) RNA sequencing, and (III) Analysis. In our experiment, analysis consists of trimming sequencing adapters from reads, checking the reads for quality control metrics, aligning the reads to a reference genome, and counting the reads on genomic intervals. Many different tools have been created for each step of the analysis pipeline; we will compare and contrast some of the main differences between popular tools/methods in a later section.

What are those? you ask? Ill allow Illumina to explain for now:

  • fastq files explained

Our job is to take these sequencing reads, align them to a reference genome (the honey bee genome, in this case), and generate a count of the number of reads mapping to gene transcripts (our measure of gene expression by RNA-seq!)

4.3 Setup

4.3.1 Bash (*the catch)

Alright, I hate to tell you this, but, no matter how hard you try to avoid it you will need to set a few things up in bash (if using a Mac, you can work in bash via Terminal). The algorithms used to align NGS reads to a reference genome are simply too resource intensive to implement in R directly, and many excellent command line tools are readily available to download and install. To make things easier for us, we will use a package management system (Conda) which will effectively reduce the number of opportunities for Murphys law to manifest. The second half of this workshop covers the world of R Markdown, wherein bash code chunks can be written and run while knitting the markdown document. Therefore it is technically possible to complete the entirety of RNA-seq and DEG analysis within R once you know things will run smoothly in bash :) More on this later

4.3.1.1 Conda

Download an installer for Miniconda here. Follow the instructions, then open a Terminal window once installation completes.

After installing conda you will need to add the bioconda channel as well as the other channels bioconda depends on. It is important to add them in this order so that the priority is set correctly (that is, conda-forge is highest priority).

The conda-forge channel contains many general-purpose packages not already found in the defaults channel. In your terminal:

conda config --add channels defaults
conda config --add channels bioconda
conda config --add channels conda-forge

Now, we need to create a Conda environment in which to install a few bioinformatics tools:

conda create -n bioinformatics

Each time you open a new Terminal window, it is operating within a base environment called .bash_profile. We want to work within our new bioinformatics Conda environment:

conda activate bioinformatics

Next, we can install most of the tools we need directly through Conda. The first of these tools are called samtools and bedtools, suites of programs for interacting with high-throughput sequencing data and for conducting operations on genomic intervals. We wont use them directly in this workshop, but they are often prerequisite for other bioinformatics tools. Next, we will use NCBIs SRA-toolkit to interface with SRA.

conda install -c bioconda samtools

conda install -c bioconda bedtools

conda install -c bioconda sra-tools

4.3.1.2 Command line tools

Additionally, we will install trim_galore, and kallisto. Trim_galore is a wrapper program around cutadapt - which is used to trim sequencing adapters from sequencing reads (more on this later) - and FastQC - which creates reports detailing quality control metrics of the sequencing reads (more on this later, too). Kallisto is the tool we will use to generate transcript abundance estimates for calculating gene expression. To install trim_galore and kallisto, follow each link (above) and associated download and install instructions.

4.4 The Short Read Archive (SRA)

Excellent - now lets get some data and run it through the pipeline! First, lets see what it looks like on the depository website. Go to https://trace.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/Traces/study/? and search the SRA Study accession SRP242105. This GUI page displays the data and metadata associated with BioProject accession PRJNA601517.

Definitions: BioProject submission describes the goal of the sequencing study, whereas the SRA Study (SRA prefix SRP) is an object that contains the project metadata describing a sequencing study or project.

The 24 rows of the SRA Run Selector spreadsheet on this page describe the 24 individual sequencing runs (SRA prefix SRR), or objects that contain actual sequencing data for a particular sequencing experiment.

Typically, if you are looking to download the sequencing data contained in each run, it is helpful to download both the Metadata and Accession List associated with the SRA Study. Below we will see how to use these files as input to the pipeline. BUT FIRST: notice how dang massive these sequencing runs are in terms of file size? The Bytes column tells us that each run is, on average, 2 Gb, with some files up to 20 Gb! WOW!

4.5 Short tutorial

Before you throw your laptop at the wall, no, Im not going to make you try to download 120+ Gb of data for this tutorial (unless you really want to). Instead, we will first work with a single, smaller run from an unrelated honey bee RNA-seq project. Then, we will work with synthetic runs I generated by sub-setting the real runs, which you can download here:

  • Synthetic SRP242105 for full tutorial

Note: total file size is ~7 Gb. I recommend downloading these on campus/etc. internet and doing so ASAP!

First, clone the workshop GitHub repository. In terminal:

# Set DIR to the directory on your local machine where you'd like to clone the repository
DIR="wherever/you/want/to/put/this/directory"
git clone https://github.com/sbresnahan/RNAseq-to-DEGs.git ${DIR}

4.5.1 Retrieve data from SRA

In the full-scale run-through, we will see how to use the Metadata and Accession List files to avoid manually typing out an array accessions, but for this tutorial, we only need to retrieve one run. Specifically, we will retrieve an RNA sequencing run (accession SRR13397503) of a honey bee brain from BioProject accession PRJNA691031 which describes a study assessing transcriptomic responses of the honey bee brain to infection with Deformed Wing Virus (DWV). This run is much smaller (~800 Mb) which should download relatively quickly. Since we are only retrieving one run, we dont really need to tell bash that were working with a list of accessions, but lets walk through the logic anyhow. In terminal:

SRA_LIST=("SRR13397503")

A bash array typically contains more than one entry, separated by spaces, e.g.:

egSRA_LIST=("SRR13397503" "SRR0000000" "SRR0000009")

Now, we want to retrieve each sequencing run listed in the array SRA_LIST by iterating over each entry in the array and issuing the sra-tools commands prefetch (to retrieve the SRR object) and fasterq-dump to split the retrieved .sra file into our paired-end sequencing reads in .fastq format. Before we do this, we should set the sra-tools download directory to the volume/external directory our cloned GitHub repository. In terminal:

EXT_DIR="${DIR}/volume/external"
echo "/repository/user/main/public/root = \"$EXT_DIR\"" > $HOME/.ncbi/user-settings.mkfg
# Note: you may want to set this back to the default directory '$HOME/ncbi/public/sra' when you are done with this project.

Now, we will tell bash to iterate over each index i of SRA_LIST and issue the prefetch and fasterq-dump commands on the entry at index i of SRA_LIST. Be sure to set the output -O flag of the latter command to EXT_DIR. Note: in bash, retrieving the value associated with an object requires referencing the object with ${object}, as object retrieves the object itself:

for i in "${SRA_LIST[@]}"; do
prefetch ${i}
fasterq-dump -O ${EXT_DIR} ${i}
done

If all goes well, you will see some output in terminal like this:

(bioinformatics) Seans-MacBook-Pro:tutorial sbresnahan$ prefetch SRR13397503  
2021-03-03T11:38:27 prefetch.2.9.3: 1) Downloading 'SRR13397503'...  
2021-03-03T11:38:27 prefetch.2.9.3:  Downloading via fasp...  
2021-03-03T11:39:32 prefetch.2.9.3:  fasp download succeed  
2021-03-03T11:39:32 prefetch.2.9.3: 1) 'SRR13397503' was downloaded successfully  
2021-03-03T11:39:32 prefetch.2.9.3: 'SRR13397503' has 0 unresolved dependencies  
  
(bioinformatics) Seans-MacBook-Pro:tutorial sbresnahan$ fasterq-dump SRR13397503  
spots read      : 8,879,024

reads written   : 17,758,048

which tells us that the SRR object was retrieved successfully and split into paired-end .fastq files containing 17,758,048 reads.

4.5.2 Trim adapters

Now that we have our .fastq files, we will trim off any adapter sequences (and assess our reads for various quality control metrics) with trim_galore:

# Go to the directory containing our .fastq files
cd ${DIR}/data/raw

# Create a list of all files ending in .fastq
FILE_LIST=*.fastq

# Call trim_galore with --fastqc flag set to run FastQC on the trimmed reads. 
# Set the -j flag to the number of threads to run on (e.g., 2-4). 
# Set the --paired flag to say we are working with paired-end reads. 
# Set the -o flag to the `volume/interim' directory of our project.
trim_galore --fastqc -j 4 --paired ${FILE_LIST[*]} -o ${DIR}/volume/interim

Since our .fastq files are named by SRR accession, they will essentially sort numerically, so we can be sure that the entries in FILE_LIST consist of mate pairs 1 and 2, respectively, for each run, one after another, which is what trim_galore --paired expects. If all goes well, you will see some output in terminal like this:

4.5.3 Quality control (FastQC)

Keep in mind, FastQC is just giving us some indicators of the overall health of NGS reads. Dont take the PASS and FAIL notifications too seriously. FastQC has a really well documented manual page with more details about all the plots in the report. Check out this post for more information on what bad plots look like and what they mean for your data.

The two most important modules in FastQC are the Per base sequence quality plot and the Overrepresented sequences table. The Per base sequence quality plot provides the distribution of quality scores across all bases at each position in the reads. Looking at this plot for SRR13397503_1_val_1.fq, we see that the mean per base sequence quality is within a passing range across the length of the reads.

FastQC Per base sequence quality plot

The Overrepresented sequences table displays the sequences (at least 20 bp) that occur in more than 0.1% of the total number of sequences. This table aids in identifying contamination, such as vector or adapter sequences.

FastQC Overrepresented sequences plot

The top 2 overrepresented sequences for SRR13397503_1_val_1.fq reveal two common sources of contamination in RNA-seq libraries: 1) poly(A) (Sangiovanni et al., 2019), and 2) mitochondrial (Ilicic et al., 2016). Why suggest that the overrepresented sequence CTAATTTTCATCTTAATTCAACATCGAGGTCGCAAACATCTTTATCTATA indicates mitochondrial contamination? And what should we/can we do if we think our libraries have been contaminated in some way? (Think about this on your own and we will discuss in class!)

4.5.3.1 Exersize: BLAST search of overrepresented sequences

It can be informative to BLAST search overrepresented sequences. Copy the sequence above, go to https://blast.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/Blast.cgi?PAGE_TYPE=BlastSearch and run a search (either megablast or blastn is fine.)

4.5.4 Read pseudo-alignment (kallisto)

Assuming everything looks alright, the final step in the pipeline (before analysis of the resultant gene expression data) is to align our reads to a reference genome and then count the number of reads that aligned across gene transcript intervals.

Arguably, this is the step that requires the most intellectual input, in part due to there being different methods of read alignment (as well as many different tools one could use to implement a given method). What we will not do in this course is technically dissect each method or give an argument about whether one particular method is better; several reviews have been written about this subject (Crochet et al., 2020). That said, lets at least talk about what the two main types of read alignment tools are - classic read alignment and pseudoalignment - and why we will use the latter in this workshop.

Contrary to normal read alignment, where we specify where the read aligns and how, i.e.how the nucleotides in the read match up with the nucleotides in the target sequence, a pseudoalignment of a read is simply a set of target sequences that the read is compatible with. A more precise definition and discussion can be found in Lior Pachters blog post, What is a read mapping.

The definition of pseudoalignment is crafted so that the output is a sufficient statistic for the basic RNA-Seq quantification model. As such, the focus is on sets of transcripts with counts rather than detailed alignments. While this makes pseudoalignments less intuitive than regular alignments, pseudoalignment tools - like kallisto - do impressively reduce the computational load, while remaining near-optimal in terms of alignment efficiency when compared to popular classical read alignment tools (Bray et al., 2016). Thus, it is the ideal method for at-home RNA-seq analysis!

Total running time in minutes for processing 20 simulated data sets of 30 million paired-end reads.

4.5.4.1 Making a kallisto reference transcriptome

In this workshop, we will use the popular pseudoalignment tool kallisto to generate counts of gene transcript abundances. In order to make the reference transcriptome for kallisto to find pseudoalignments on, we need the honey bee gene transcript sequences themselves. How do we get these? From the honey bee reference genome, of course!

Step 1: download a copy of the most recent honey bee reference genome (HAv3.1(Wallberg et al., 2019)) from NCBI in .fasta format. What is .fasta format? Think .fastq, minus all of the information that would only be relevant given the sequence in question has come from an NGS machine. See a detailed description of the .fasta format here.
In your terminal:

GENOME_FILE=/volume/external/GCF_003254395.2_Amel_HAv3.1_genomic.fna.gz
wget -O ${GENOME_FILE} https://ftp.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/genomes/all/GCF/003/254/395/GCF_003254395.2_Amel_HAv3.1/GCF_003254395.2_Amel_HAv3.1_genomic.fna.gz

If you unzip the file and open it in a text browser, youll see one FASTA entry for each of the honey bee chromosomes. How do we pull out just the gene transcript sequences? First, well need a special type of data file called a General Feature Format (GFF) file, which describes genes and other features of DNA, RNA and protein sequences. At the most basic level, its a file where each row corresponds to one genomic feature, detailing information about, most importantly: i) which chromosome it is on, ii) what kind of feature it is, and iii) its genomic interval, or START and STOP coordinates on the chromosome.

Step 2: download a copy of the HAv3.1 GFF file from NCBI.
In your terminal:

GFF_FILE=/volume/external/GCF_003254395.2_Amel_HAv3.1_genomic.gff.gz
wget -O ${GFF_FILE} https://ftp.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/genomes/all/GCF/003/254/395/GCF_003254395.2_Amel_HAv3.1/GCF_003254395.2_Amel_HAv3.1_genomic.gff.gz

Both files are compressed .gz archives, which we need to decompress.

Step 3: gunzip both files:

gunzip ${GENOME_FILE}
gunzip ${GFF_FILE}

Now, we will use a dependency of bedtools, which we installed earlier, to extract the gene transcript sequences from the .fasta reference genome file using the intervals specified in the .gff file.

Step 4: call gffread to extract the gene transcript sequences.
In terminal:

GENOME_FILE=/volume/external/GCF_003254395.2_Amel_HAv3.1_genomic.fna
GFF_FILE=/volume/external/GCF_003254395.2_Amel_HAv3.1_genomic.gff
CDS_FILE=/volume/external/Amel_Hav3.1_transcripts.fasta

gffread ${GFF_FILE} -g ${GENOME_FILE} -w ${OUT_FILE} -F

Step 5: finally, call kallisto index to build the reference transcriptome alignment index using our CDS_FILE:

kallisto index --make-unique -i kallisto_Amel_HAv3.1 Amel_HAv3.1_transcripts.fasta
